    "summary": "The Battle of Plataea (479 BC) was the final major land engagement of the second Persian invasion of Greece, resulting in a decisive Greek victory that ended Persian ambitions of conquest on the European mainland. A combined Greek army under the Spartan regent Pausanias — the largest Greek force ever assembled — met the Persian army under Mardonius near the city of Plataea in Boeotia.\n\nMardonius had wintered in Thessaly after [[event:1005|Battle of Salamis]] and invaded Attica again in spring, forcing the Athenians to once more evacuate their city. The Greek alliance finally mustered a force of around 40,000 heavily armed hoplites plus a larger number of light troops and helots. After days of maneuvering and supply-line harassment, a confused night withdrawal by the Greeks turned into a disorganized rout that Mardonius exploited by ordering a charge. The Spartan contingent held firm, cut down Mardonius in personal combat, and the Persian army collapsed and fled to their fortified camp, which was subsequently stormed.",
